      "* Think of it like throwing pebbles (blue light) and bowling balls (red light) at a bumpy surface. The pebbles are much more likely to bounce off in different directions.\n",
      "\n",
      "\n",
      "**4. Why We See Blue (and not Violet)?**\n",
      "\n",
      "* **Violet is scattered *even more* than blue.** However, there are a couple of reasons we predominantly see blue:\n",
      "    * **Sunlight emits less violet light than blue light.**\n",
      "    * **Our eyes are more sensitive to blue light than violet light.**\n",
      "\n",
      "**In simpler terms:** The air molecules scatter blue light in all directions, so no matter where you look in the sky, some of this scattered blue light reaches your eyes.\n",
      "\n",
      "**What about sunsets?**\n",
      "\n",
      "At sunrise and sunset, the sunlight has to travel through *much more* of the atmosphere to reach your eyes.  Because the blue light has been scattered away by the time the sunlight gets to you, the longer wavelengths like orange and red are able to make it through, creating the beautiful sunset colors.\n",
      "\n",
      "\n",
      "\n",
      "**Resources for Further Learning:**\n",
